text:
The issue of high-temperature thermal hazards is an unavoidable challenge in deep mine extraction. The underground temperature increases with mining depth, leading to adverse conditions in the working environment of deep mines. This not only reduces equipment performance and shortens its lifespan but also negatively impacts the working capacity and health of underground personnel, increasing the likelihood of production accidents. The main causes of thermal hazards in mines include: 

1) Heat release from surrounding rock. The temperature of the surrounding rock increases with depth below the surface, causing a heat exchange between normal-temperature airflow and high-temperature surrounding rock, resulting in elevated temperatures; 
2) Adiabatic heating of air. Air entering the mine shaft from the surface transforms into thermal energy due to friction under its own gravitational influence, increasing its temperature at an adiabatic heating rate of 9.8°C/km; 
3) Heat release from electrical and mechanical equipment; 
4) Heat generated by mineral oxidation. The fracturing of rock layers during mining produces fissures, and the reaction of minerals with oxygen generates heat; 
5) Heat release from geothermal water in the mine. Under the influence of the geothermal heat flow field, deep groundwater is heated to form high-temperature mine water, which causes changes in underground temperature through direct heating of airflow or heat transfer from rock; 
6) Other factors that release heat. For example, heat generated from backfill in goaf areas, human body heat, explosive heat, and climatic changes can also contribute to the increase in mine temperature to varying degrees. 

As mining depth increases, heat release from surrounding rock, adiabatic heating of airflow, mineral oxidation, and geothermal water heating will significantly intensify, making thermal hazards in mines more severe and their control increasingly challenging.
